definition.value: An N(4)-glycosylated asparagine residue in which the glycan moiety is a branched octasaccharide consisting of five D-mannosyl residues and three N-acetylglucosamine residues, one of which at the reducing end is bonded to the asparagine N(4) atom.

An N(4)-glycosylated asparagine residue in which the glycan moiety is a branched decasaccharide consisting of eight D-mannosyl residues and two N-acetylglucosamine residues, one of which at the reducing end is bonded to the asparagine N(4) atom.

An N(4)-glycosylated asparagine residue in which the glycan moiety is a branched decasaccharide consisting of eight D-mannosyl residues and two N-acetylglucosamine residues, one of which at the reducing end is bonded to the asparagine N(4) atom.

An N(4)-glycosylated asparagine residue in which the glycan moiety is a branched decasaccharide consisting of eight D-mannosyl residues and two N-acetylglucosamine residues, one of which at the reducing end is bonded to the asparagine N(4) atom.
The pentanoate anion substituted at the alpha-carbon by a hydroxy group.  The conjugate base of 2-hydroxypentanoic acid, it is the predominant species at physiological pH.
The S-enantiomer of 2-hydroxy-3-methylbutyric acid. It is used as a chiral building block for peptide synthesis.
An acetyl group (CHEBI:40574) attached to a nitrogen atom
The tetraethyl ester of [[(3-hydroxypyridin-2-yl)amino]methylene]bisphosphonic acid

A member of the class of pyrrolidin-2-ones that is pyrrolidin-2-one in which the 3-pro-S-hydrogen is substituted by a 2-methoxy-2-oxoethyl group, while the 5-pro-S-hydrogen is substituted by a ({4'-[N-(methoxycarbonyl)carbamimidoyl]biphenyl-4-yl}oxy)methyl group. It is an orally active prodrug of fradafiban, a figrinogen receptor antagonist.
Ethanone substituted at C-1 by a (2-trifluoromethoxyphenyl group and at C-2 by a nitro group.
A 4-aryl-5-(2-hydroxyalkyl)pyridine derivative used as a glucagon receptor antagonist.

An N(4)-glycosylated asparagine residue in which the glycan moiety is a branched nonasaccharide consisting of seven D-mannosyl residues and two N-acetylglucosamine residues, one of which at the reducing end is bonded to the asparagine N(4) atom.
Any ester of a delta-amino acid.
A member of the class of 2,5-diketopiperazines obtained via autoaminolysis of amoxicillin.

An N(4)-glycosylated asparagine residue in which the glycan moiety is a branched nonasaccharide consisting of seven D-mannosyl residues and two N-acetylglucosamine residues, one of which at the reducing end is bonded to the asparagine N(4) atom.

The hydrochloride salt of methyl 5-aminolevulinate. A prodrug, it is metabolised to protoporphyrin IX, a photosensitizer, and is used in the photodynamic treatment of non-melanoma skin cancer (including basal cell carcinoma). Topical application results in an accumulation of protoporphyrin IX in the skin lesions to which the cream has been applied. Subsequent illumination with red light results in the generation of toxic singlet oxygen that destroys cell membranes and thereby kills the tumour cells.

Any substance that inhibits the action of N-methyl-D-aspartate (NMDA) receptors. They tend to induce a state known as dissociative anesthesia, marked by catalepsy, amnesia, and analgesia, while side effects can include hallucinations, nightmares, and confusion. Due to their psychotomimetic effects, many NMDA receptor antagonists are used as recreational drugs.
Any organic aromatic compound containing two phenyl (or substituted phenyl) groups attached to a single carbon or heteroatom and which has significant antifungal properties.
A valine derivative that is valine in which the amino group has been replaced by a hydroxy group.
A chiral compound used to induce stereoselectivity into a reaction.
A 2-hydroxy monocarboxylic acid that is valeric (pentanoic) acid substituted at the alpha-position by a hydroxy group.

The monohydrate form of doxycycline. A semi-synthetic tetracycline antibiotic, it is used to inhibit bacterial protein synthesis and treat non-gonococcal urethritis and cervicitis, exacerbations of bronchitis in patients with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), and adult periodontitis.
An agent which blocks glucagon receptors.
A linear trisaccharide, which forms part of the repeating unit of the Salmonella serogroup B oligosaccharide.

An N(4)-glycosylated asparagine residue in which the glycan moiety is a branched heptasaccharide consisting of three D-mannosyl residues and four N-acetylglucosamine residues, one of which at the reducing end is bonded to the asparagine N(4) atom.

The purified component of haematoporphyrin derivative, it consists of a mixture of oligomeric porphyrins formed by ether and ester linkages of up to eight porphyrin units (n = 0-6), where R = CH(OH)Me and/or CH=CH2.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the phosphatidyl acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are stearoyl and oleoyl respectively.
A branched-chain saturated fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of valproic acid.
A polyprenylhydroquinone in which the polyprenyl substituent is octaprenyl at C-2; a methoxy group is also present at C-6.
A polyprenylhydroquinone in which the polyprenyl substituent is octaprenyl at C-3; methoxy and methyl groups are also present at C-5 and C-2 respectively.
The conjugate base of prostaglandin E2; major species at pH 7.3.
An alpha-amino-acid anion that is the conjugate base of N-benzoylglycine; major species at pH 7.3.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the phosphatidyl acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are both arachidonoyl.
A 4,6-O-[(1R)-1-carboxyethylidene]-D-galactose having alpha-configuration at the anomeric centre.
The univalent carboacyl group formed by loss of -OH from the carboxy group of 5-chloropentanoic acid.
The aroyl group formed by loss of -OH from the carboxy group of 2-(trifluoromethyl)benzoic acid.
The aroyl group formed by loss of -OH from the carboxy group of 3-(trifluoromethyl)benzoic acid.
The aroyl group formed by loss of -OH from the carboxy group of 4-(trifluoromethyl)benzoic acid.
The aroyl group formed by loss of -OH from the carboxy group of 2,5-bis(trifluoromethyl)benzoic acid.
The aroyl group formed by loss of -OH from the carboxy group of 4-bromobenzoic acid.
The aroyl group formed by loss of -OH from the carboxy group of 2-iodobenzoic acid.
A polythiophene polymer, composed of poly(2,2'-bithiophene-5,5'-diyl) macromolecules.
The univalent carboacyl group formed by loss of -OH from the carboxy group of 6-bromohexanoic acid.
The univalent carboacyl group formed by loss of -OH from the carboxy group of chloroacetic acid.

A retinoic acid that is all-trans-retinoic acid in which the double bond which is alpha,beta- to the carboxy group is isomerised to Z configuration. A synthetic retinoid, it is used for the treatment of severe cases of acne and other skin diseases.
The univalent carboacyl group formed by loss of -OH from the carboxy group of (2,2,2-trifluoroethoxy)acetic acid.
